{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_eustachy_ver01/data/sn83030214/00206532580/1920121501/0447.xml":{"full_text":"Society Folk\nKept Busy as\nMany Entertain\nLuncheons, Bridge Parties,\nDinners and Danees Fill\nDays With Activity for\nMatrons and Debutantes\nMusicales Are Popular\nMrs. Chas. E. Mitchell Gives\nPrivate Recital in Home;\nCharity Ball February 1\nLuncheons, bridge parties, dinners,\ndances, musicales and entertainments\nfor charity made yesterday a stren?\nuous one for society. Mr. and Mrs.\nCharles E. Mitchell, of 933 Fifth Ave?\nnue, gave a musicale lest night at\ntheir home, at which Rafaelo Diaz,\ntenor of the Metropolitan Opera House\nsang and .Miss Mae Mukie, 'cellist'\nplayed.\nMr. and Mrs. C. Ledyard Blair gave\na small dinner and dance at their\nhouse, i East Seventieth Street.\nF.ar:'>r in the day Miss Kliz.-.beth\n?nd Miss Lilian Rbmsen, ?laughters of\nMr. and Mrs. Charles Rerasen, gave a\nluncheon in the Fail Mall Room of\ntha Riti-Carlton. Their guests, about\nfifty in number, included Mrs. Martin\nW. Littleton jr. Mrs. Henry Coster\nSteers, Mrs. John F. Hubbard, Mrs.\nGeorge Henry Warren jr., Mrs. Her?\nman C. Schwab, Mis< Mary Van\nt?nsselaer Lorillardi Miss Elizabeth\nChap?n. Miss Helen Trevor. Miss A.\nRouth Ogden, Miss Belle Baruch, Miss\nSylvia Hillhouse, .??Si Gladys Liyer\njnore, Miss Mary Crocker, Miss Eliza?\nbeth Chisholm, Miss Adelaide Kin\nBhinelander, Miss Molly Van Rensse\nlaer Cogswell, Miss Marcrarot Flint,\nMiss Alice de L?mar and Miss Evange\nline Brewster Johnson.\nMrs. Robert Ralston Crosby enter?\ntained at luncheon yesterday in the\nsmall ballroom on the secon?! floor of\nDelmonico's. The guests, about forty\nMiss Genevi?ve Clendenin\nShe is one of the many members of the younger set actively working to\nmake the annual concert of the Catholic Big Brothers, December 26\nat the Hippodrome, a big success.\nf.\nin number, who afterward played j\ni bridge, included Mrs. Frederick Roose\nvelt. Mrs. J. Henry Dick. Mrs. Horace.\nC. Du Val, Mrs. Justus Ruperti, Mrs.\nWa'ter L. Suydam, Mrs. Alfred Wag\nstaff, Mrs. H. Sellers McKee, Mrs. Ed\nward B. Clifford Chisolm, Mrs. E/Ly-j\nman Short, Mrs. Wesley Watson, Mr3.\nMalcolm Stuart, Mrs. Robert Watson,\nMrs. Frederick Stimson, Mrs. Samuel\nValentine, Mrs* Courtlandt Van\nms'selaer, Mrs. Jfjin B. Stanchfield,\nTHE BOSTON GIFT BOOK\nof 1920 is\nThe Crooked and Narrow\nStreets o? the Town of\nBoston 1620-1822\nBv ANNIE HAVEN THWING\nBe Sure to See It!\nPrice $5.00\nMARSHALL JONES CO., Pushers\n212 Summer Street, Boston\n?fp^ptttnain\nf !&e; Bookstore\n2wes145Tst.'iairf5A?NT'\nFor (hristmas\nWhen in doubt, buy a\nBook Certificate\n?'??'??'.??-??.i.-.?.i i i??\nand let your friend make\nhis own selection\n$5.00 to $5000.\n:?j X tery and a ma nee\n:h Santa ?\"laus\nfcj tobring them With a\nH Bad Name-.' A fascina\ngj 7 an ntii\nkind, bj I y Poore\nj BLASCO IBANEZ' nove!\nThe Enemies\nof Women\nby the author of t I hrsemon\nof the Apocalypse.\" $2.1 5. If not in\njrom local re, can be had from\nE. P. DUTTON CO., 631 5th At., N. T.\nI ??rpHE Hou With a Bad Name'.'\nS A ped 'in a seen\nenser and\nBucceed\n?i\ntor lystery\n83 ?wry of ai v novel kir!. by\nP PttUrf Poor*- She All boo Its tores.\nFOR CHRISTMAS CIVE A NOVEL\nBy MEERICK his\nL'miorm wlh \"Conrad in Qutst of i lis\nYouth.\" $1.90. If not in your local\nbc^k ?tor'', il ran be hari from\nP. Din TON CO., 681 5th At., N. Y.\nA MY8TEBYI??\nW Black who\na ?.?tine ?rid\nEngen?, ?ho blackmails the old but?\nin ?to? h? becomes her\nweapon? Aod ??anger still??no\n?m i.e.- father? Who ?was her\n_ SVi'f.? .V-a?.' do tbe? 'oreatt-n\niiead ?he House With\nM all bookstores.\n<i222ZZ2?Z%Z^7;^^Z2iZ2^72i2^\n?*r?rj /over of Opera thould own\nth'n book\nComplete Opera Book\nBy 00s/Cs\\T KOKK?\n1000 Pages, 100 Illu-t'stiort?, 400\nMur?.? I .'viola/'?. The moil com\nf?f?h<t??tve, authoritative, up-to-?date\nwork ?rver ussicd on this ?ur-je/ t. ??.00\nBOOXMTOSBM PUTNAM?\nS*n> WretncUe? Chicago York\nTHE ONE QUESTION