.)\nALFRED A. KNOPF, 220 W. 42d STREET, NEW YORK\nPromises Friend Suit-a-Child,\nCalls Pledge Off. at Fourteenth\nNorth Carolina Representative Made Agreement\nWhen Farmer Had Twenty Children, Now He\nHas Thirty-four and Still Fears Stork\nWASHINGTON, N. C, Dec! 14.?For\nmany years Representative Small, of\nNorth Carolina, by agreement, has been j\npresenting to R. C. Bland, a Carolina\nfarmer and one of his constituents, a j\nnew suit of clothes for each additional\nchild in his famly. Having presented\nthirteen suits and being recently noti?\nfied to send the fourteenth, Represent?\native Small has informed Bland that\nthe contract will be off with Mr. Small's\nretirement from Congress, on March 3.\nSmall and Bland made their compact\nseveral years ago, when Small was mak?\ning a campaign speech at Roherson\nville, near here. Bland then had\ntwenty children; he now has thirty\nfour.\nTwenty-six Are Living\nTwenty-six of the thirty-four Bland\nchildren are living, and the present\nMrs. Bland, Bland's second wife, is the\nmother of nineteen, nine of whom were\nborn during the last ten years, inifiud\ning one set of twins. Eighteen children\nstill live at home, but ?Mrs. Bland de?\nclares she gets lonesome sometimes\n\"because so many have gone away.\"\nMr. a-nd Airs. Bland recently had a\ngroup photograph taken of the family\nstill remaining on the Bland farm.\nWhile the photographer was working\na buzzard cast its shadow on the\nground. Bland was asked if he was\nsuperstitious.\n\"No,\" he said, \"I'm not afraid of buz-\nzards, but at first I thought the blame\nthing was a stork.\"\nIn calling the children together for\nthe photograph Bland simply cupped\n?his hands and in a stentorian voice\ncried: \"Children!\"\nResults were immediate.\nChildren appeared from every direc?\ntion. Some of the children were grown\nmen and women; others were barely\nable to toddle forth and one still was\nbeing carried in arms.\nWhen You Pass Ten It's Easy\nBland says it is no more trouble to\nbring up fifty children than it is to\nraise ten.\n\"After you pass ten,\" he says, \"the\nolder ones are a great help.\"\nThe children were not unusually\nnoisy, Blahd said,.although \"they made\nconsiderable racket when fourteen were\ntaken down together with whooping\ncough.\" The Bland grocery bill is\nequivalent to about $150 a week, al?\nthough Bland produces a large part of\nhis food. On one occasion he says he\nspent most of one night computing the\ncost of keeping his family comfortable,\nbut that the figures reached such alarm?\ning proportions he gave up the job.\nBland is sixty-five years old.\nMrs. Wilbcr A. Bloodgood and Mri,\nStephen U. Williams.\nMrs. Richard Stevens, who is at\nCastle Point, Hoboken, has recalled!\nthe invitations for the dinner she was\nto have given Friday night at the\nHotel St. Regis for her debutante\ndaughter, Miss Dorothy Stevens, owing\nto the death of her eldest daughter,\nMiss Elsie Stevens. Mrs. Robert\nStevens also has withdrawn her invita?\ntions for a dinner dance which whs\nto have been ?riven at the Ritz-Carlton\nMonday night to introduce her daugh?\nter, Miss Mary S. Stevens.\nMr. and Mrs. Ambrose Hammet\nBurroughs, of Woodland, Irvington-on\nHudson. announce the engagement of\ntheir daughter. Miss Florence Bur?\nroughs, to William Montrose Tottis,\nonly son of Mr. and Mrs. Clifton I).\nPettis, of Chicago and New York. The\nwedding will take place in the spring.\nMr. and Mrs. Frederick Taylor Hep?\nburn, of Flushing, L. I., will give a\ndance December 21 to introduce their\nI daughter, Miss Mary Hepburn.\nMiss Elizabeth Warren Murphy, only\ndaughter of Mr. and Mrs. Richard F.\nMurphy, of 115 East Eighty-second\ni Street, will be introduced to society at\na dansant which her grandmother, Mrs.\nI. McConihe, will give for her at the\nPlaza January 1. Mis? Murphy is a\ngranddaughter of Edward Murphy, of\nTroy, formerly United States Sen?\nator, and is a niece of ex-Judge War?\nren McConihe.\n\n\"Faust\" to Open Week\nAt Metropolitan Opera\n\"Faust\" will begin the sixth week of\nI tl- Metropolitan Opera season with\nMmes. Farrar, Berat and Delaunois\nand Mess's. Harrold, Danise, Rothier\nand Ananian, Mr. Wolff conducting,\nother operas next week will be:\n\"Elisir d'Amore\" on Wednesday eve\nning, with Mmes. Garrison and Ellis\na* d Messrs. Caruso, Scotti and Mala\ntesta. Mr. Papi will conduct.\n\"Don Carlos,\" the fourth in the list\nI of Mr. Gatti's \"novelties and revivals,\"\nwill be given for the lirst time at the\nMetropolitan Opera House Thursday\nevening, the cast including Mmes. Pon\nselle, Matzenauer and Sundelius and\nMessrs. Martinelli, De Luca and Didur.\nMis, Galli and Mr. Monfiglio will dance.\nMr. l'api will conduct.\n\"Madama Butterfly\" on Friday after?\nnoon with Mines, Farrar, Fornia and\nEgener and Messrs. Chamlee and Scotti.\n\"La Juive\" on Friday evening, with\nM...es. Easton and Scotney and Messrs.\nI Caruso, Harrold and Rothier.\n\"Mefistofele\" will be the Saturday\nmatinee opera, with Mmes, Alda, Peralta,\nHoward and Perini and Messrs. Gigli\ni?r d Mardones.\nVasa Prihoda, violinist, will be the\nvisiting artist at next Sunday night's\n\"opera concert.\" Mmes. Garrison and\nGo~don and Mr. Chamlee will sing and\nthe Metropolitan orchestra will take\npart, under the direction of Giuseppe\nBamb?schek.\nOn Monday afternoon, December 27,\n\"The Blue Bird\" will be sung for the\nI first time this season. Popular prices\nwill prevail.\n\"Tristan and Isoida\" will be given at\nthe Academy of Music, Brooklyn, Tuesday\nevening, December 21, the cast includ?\ning Mmes. Easton and Gordon and\nMessrs. Sembach, Whitehill. Gustafson,\nDiaz, Dua, Loon hard and D'Angelo. Mr.\nBodanzky will conduct.\nHeinz Collection on Sa'e\nThe Henry J. Heinz collection, in\neluding ivory carvings, Chinese jade,\nlacquers, enamels and other .art objects,\nis being sold at auction at the American\nI Art Galleries this week. The first ses?\nsion yesterday amounted to $5,663.\nj Books belonging to Mr. Heinz were sold\nMonday evening for a total of $4,318.50.\nj The sales yesterday afternoon in\nI eluded\nj ??old rlnR watch, ?ctaRnnal face, studded\nwith turquoise, and with minuto porcelain\ndial and works exposed at crown; F. Bau?\nmeister, $145.\nJeweled pold bc?-tle watch. ??Ivor and\nenamel wlnns. studded with chip diamonds;\nF. Baumeister, $170.\nSilwr gilded enamel watch nnd ohat\"\nlaine, outer cas--> enriched with subject\n1 \"Aetaeon ami His Hounds; H. Symons;\n?120.\n.toweled silver glldeil lorgnette, flat fili\nI gree baluster liun.ll\", set with various\npear's, diamond? nnd other precious stones;\nF. Baumeister; $136.\nSculptured coral reliquary, Italian, sev\ni enteeuth century, from tho Yerkes collec\ntlon; H. Martin; $230.\nJeweled silver statuette, standing- figure\nof a medioeval bride; F. Baumelster; $175.\nThe sales will continue every after\nnoon this week at the American Art\nGalleries at 2 o'clock.\nO'Brien Sale Nets $6,413\nThe second part of the library of Dr.\nFrank P. O'Brien sold at the Anderson\ngalleries yesterday and Monday brought\na total of $6,413.55. The final sale yes\nterday amounted to $1,625.20.\nContinuing This Afternoon\nUNRESTRICTED PUBLIC SALE\nOF\nEXTRAORDINARY IMPORTANCE\n0?\n??iJMNSaUARESoimi |W^J NEW ?URK. CUY\nBY ORDER OF EXECUTORS\nTHIS WEDNESDAY\nThursday, Friday Saturday\nAfternoon at 2 o'clock\nTHE VERY EXTENSIVE\nART COLLECTION\nFORMED BY THR LATE\nHENRY J. HEINZ\nOF PITTSm'Ri;, I'ENNA.\nWHICH INCLUDES\nA Remarkable Gathering of\nEuropean and Oriental Ivory\nCarvings, Many Beautiful\nChinese Jades and Crystals\nA Large Collection of Netsukes\nand Inros, Antique Soapstone Statu?\nettes, Cinnabar and other Lacquers,\nMandarin Robes, Chinese Palace\nand Temple Hangings and Furni?\nture, Fuchien China, Chinese Paint?\nings, Important Oriental Bronzes,\nCloisonne Enamels, Furniture, Fine\nOriental Rugs and Numerous Other\nObjects of Antiquity and Artistic\nInterest.\nNOW ON FREE VIEW 1> A. M. to 6 P. M.\nON FREE VIEW\nTO-DAY (WEDNESDAY)\nFROM 1) A. M. FNTIE 4 V. M.\nON THE PREMISES\nNo. 50 Riverside Drive\n(N. E. CORNER OF 77TH STREET)\nTO BE SOLD\nTOMORROW (THURS.)& FRIDAY\nOF THIS WEEK, AT 10:30 A. M.\nTHE HANDSOME\nFurnishings\nand Embellishments\n?V THE TIFFANY STUDIOS, W. St 3.\n8I.OANE AM) OTHEIt FIRST CI.ASS\nESTAB I.I S1 IM ENTN\nCONTAINED IN THE\nPRIVATE RESIDENCE OF\nMr. Albert E. Smith\nThe (Salen Will lie Conductivl by\nMR. THOMAS E. lilltllY\nund Ills ushUljuil? of the\nAMERICAN ART ASSOCIATION,\nManagers,\n2, 4 and 0 K.ix? 33rd St.. Miuliwtn Bq. South.\n\nl'YKONL?; Is un .maint ft\nMBLIS8INB TYltONC is\nnml lowly a lioroln?\nKniri\"! I hr> p/iiri\") of n novel.\nEntrone Tluokhnnnon los?w his heart\nto nor tli? moment the ni<-pn tliroii-rh\nthp doorway of the my'torious hou?u\non Olnnumon Street--\"Th<> llouae With\na )la<l Nnnu.\" which grow? tensar\nnnd moro hnffllnir with ?aeh chsptur. g\n-?At ?II bookstores, r\n?\"Hendrik William\nVan Loon's new history\nbook is as gond reading1\nfor kids as H. G. Wells'si\nis for us old folks; and;\npretty good for us o. f.,\ntoo.\"\nYou couldn't do better\nthan present a copy of\nHENDRIK VAN LOON'S\n(Chock-full of full-page colored\npictures and animated maps)\nto every \"kid\" you know?\nand a few \"old folks,\" too!\n$3.00 everywhere\nBONI LIVERIGHT, NEW YORK\nA Bog-Day\nBy WALTER EMAtfUEL\nA delightful absurdity and\ndelightfully illustrated by\nCECIL ALDIN\nPrecisely the thing to give\nwith chuckles to the owner\nof \"a precious pest.\" $1.00\nIf It Is not on sale In your\nhook store It can he had (rom\nE. P. Dutton Co., 681 5th Ave., N. Y.\nProsecutor May Act\nIn Science Church!\nInquiry by To-night\nRorke Says He Should Know\nTo-day Whether He will\nMove Against Anyone 7 j\nMore Witnesses Examined j\nSeven more witnesses were examined\nby Assistant District Attorney Korke\nyesterday in his effort to determine\nwhether the charges made by Campbell\nMacCulloch that valuable correspon?\ndence and other papers had beer, stole,\".\nfrom his desk were true. Mr. Rorke,\nlust night, reiterated his determina?\ntion not to mix in the ecclesiastical\naffairs of the church. He said more j\nwitnesses would be examined to-day I\nand that he should know by to-night i\nwhether criminal action will be taken\nagainst any one. i?\nSince the bringing of the MacCul- j\nloch charges opponents of t?ie present\ndirectorate of the Mother Church, in\nBoston, have charged that an elaborate j\nsystem of espionage is maintained.\nConcerning this allegation Albert P.\nGilmore, of the Christian Science com?\nmittee on publication, said:\n''As the committee on publication\nfot the State of New York I am con?\nvinced that the charge that a spy sys?\ntem exists in the Church is, altogether\ngroundless. If there were such a sys?\ntem it seems very likely that I should\nknow of it, as my duty leads me to\ndirect the publicity of the move?\nment for the state. That I am\na 'paid agent for the board of\ndirectors is not true. The committee\non publication is appointed by and is\nin the employment of the Christian\nScience churches of New York State\nand is paid by them, all in accordance\nwith the provisions of the manu:?!\nwhich define the duties of the office.\n\"It would be my duty to correct false\nstatements regarding the Board of Di?\nrectors, or any other Christian Scien?\ntists, appearing in the press of New\nYork State. Of the important letter\nfrom General Streeter which Mr. Mc\nCulloch claims was taken from his\ndesk I have never heard until it ap?\npeared in the press. That the present\nsituation in First, Church, New York\nCity, is the outgrowth of the litigation\nnow going on in the movement has no\nbasis in fact.\"\nB. Palmer Lewis, Christian Science\npractitioner, with offices in the Mar\nbridge Building, at Broadway arid\nThirty-fourth Street, was elected last\nnight by the congregation of the First\nChurch of Christ Scientist, to first\nreader, succeeding Campbell McCul\n1 loth. lie was elected on thr second\nballot.\nDebutantes as Usheresses\nPRINCETON, N. J., Dec. 14.?When\nthe Princeton Triangle Show comes to\nj New York to present its 1920 produc\ntion, entitled \"They Never Come Back,\"\nthirteen New York debutantes will act\nas usheresses. The performances will\nbe given Saturday afternoon and cven\ning at the Waldorf.\nThe girls are Misses Marion Taylor,\nMolly Cogswell, Josephine Cotton,\ni Betty Barber, Louise Barber, Catherine\n1 Watseen-, Clavie Reynolds, Laura Har\nding, Frances Isham, Sarah Sage, Kafch\nerine Francis, Cathleen Crawford and\nSusan Cott?.\nSeven New Yorkers have parts in the\nshow, including Edwin 11. Wever,\npresident of the Triangle Club and au\nthor of the book and most of the lyrics,\nwho will appear as Sir Rollover Doyle.\nWever made one of the hits of the\nshow in last winter's play.\nEgyptian Art Is Exhibited\nThe sixth room of the Egyptian de\npartment of the Metropolitan Museum\nof Art contains an interesting display\nof findings of the museum's Egyptian\nI expedition. This latest group of mu\nI scum pieces to be put on view includes\ni discoveries made in an unexplored tomb\nnear Thebes.\nA number of models cf daily activi-\nties taken from the tomb of Prince\nMehenkwetre are among the objects in\nthis now display. They are considered\none of the most important finds of the\nexpedition. They represent activities\nin the dead prince's life, scenes from\nhi.- garden, his granary and his stables.\nwhich were placed in the tomb with a\nview to the great dignitary's having the\n??iise of such things in his future life.\nThe models found in the tomb had to\nbe divided with the National .Museum\nin Cairo.\nGoing On To-dav\nel\nDAY\nAmerican Museum of .Natural History; ad?\nmission tree.\nMetropolitan Museum of Art; admission\nfree.\nZoological Varie; admission fro?.\nVan Cortlandt Park, admission free.\nAquarium; admission free.\nI.?.mala an o? ?la? New York Electrical\nLeague, Hotel Astor, 12:30 o'clock. 